Zhang Guangjun was appointed vice governor of Guangdong Province.
The fifth meeting of the Standing Committee of the 13th Guangdong Provincial People's Congress held its second plenary meeting in Guangzhou on 30 July.
The meeting voted to appoint Zhang Guangjun as vice governor of the Guangdong Provincial People's Government.
Previously, Zhang Guangjun served as Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the China Academy of Engineering Physics.
Comrade Zhang Guangjun's resume: Zhang Guangjun, male, Han nationality, born in February 1968, from Chongqing, joined the party in April 1994, joined the work in July 1991, graduated from the Department of Radio Engineering of Harbin Institute of Technology, majoring in electronic instruments and measurement technology, university degree, senior engineer, expert enjoying special government allowance of the State Council.
He is currently the Vice Governor of Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the Party Leadership Group.
From 1987 to 1991, he studied electronic instruments and measurement technology at the Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin Institute of Technology
From 1991 to 1998, he was a technician, deputy director of the office, secretary of the party branch and deputy director of the general engineering research institute of the China Academy of Engineering Physics
From 1998 to 2002, he was the deputy director and deputy secretary of the Party Committee of the Institute of General Engineering of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during which he concurrently served as the secretary of the Discipline Inspection Committee of the Institute from 1999.05 to 2000.12, and studied at the advanced training course for prefectural and departmental cadres of the Party School of the Sichuan Provincial Party Committee from 2001.09 to 2001.12)
From 2002 to 2002, he was Secretary of the Party Committee and Deputy Director of the Institute of General Engineering, China Academy of Engineering Physics (during the period: 2002.03-2004.05 Postgraduate Course in Management Science and Engineering, School of Management, Fudan University)
From 2002 to 2009, he was the director of the Political Department, the director of the Party Committee Office, and the vice president of the Party School of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during the period: 2005.09-2006.01 The training course for young and middle-aged cadres of the Central Party School)
2009-2014 Director of the Major Special Management Office of China Academy of Engineering Physics (during the period: 2011.09-2012.01 Training Course for Young and Middle-aged Cadres at the Central Party School)
From 2014 to 2015, he was the assistant to the president of the China Academy of Engineering Physics and the director of the Major Project Management Office
From 2015 to 2018, he served as Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of China Academy of Engineering Physics
In September 2018, he was appointed as Vice Governor of Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the Party Leadership Group
According to British media, Admiral William Moran, US Deputy Chief of Naval Operations, said that even as the US Navy is reinvigorating its forces to deal with Russia's growing concern on both sides of the Atlantic, the United States continues to focus its Navy on the Asia-Pacific region -- the Pentagon's expansion of the region -- to include the Indian Ocean, Asia, and the Pacific.
According to a report on the website of Britain's "Jane's Defense Weekly" on 24 September, the United States listed China and Russia as strategic competitors in its new national defense strategy announced at the beginning of the year.
After that, the US Navy restored the Second Fleet in order to more directly counter the activities of Russia.
The moves have raised some questions and concerns among allies and analysts who fear that the U.S. Navy may move away from the "Asia-Pacific rebalance" strategy that marks the Obama administration, the report said.
But Admiral Moran said the U.S. Navy's focus remains on the western Pacific.
Speaking at a roundtable discussion titled "Addressing the High Seas Challenge" hosted by the National Asian Research Agency in Washington, D.C., on January 24, 2018, he said: "For us, there are no major changes. ”
Moran said: "The focus is still on rebalancing, shifting the center of gravity or whatever you want to describe it. ”
He acknowledged, however, that the United States has close ties with Europe.
"We will continue to focus on growth on the West Coast and balance what we can," he said. ”
While Moran noted that the general policy regarding Russia falls within the purview of the US Secretary of Defense, he warned: " Russians may face demographic and economic challenges, but history has shown that if we come into conflict with them, they will be very tough . ”
As part of the U.S. comeback against Russia, China and other competitors, the U.S. Navy is dynamically deploying forces into a "new mode of warfare" that will help catch adversaries off guard against where U.S. carrier battle groups or other assets will be deployed at any given time and place, Admiral Moran said.
He said: "We in the Navy and the Marine Corps support it -- the concept of unpredictability of operations, not to be in the same place again and again, almost like clockwork -- that's how we do it." ”
The first to try this new approach was the USS Harry S. Truman, whose early deployment included working visits to ports and patrols in areas that would normally only pass through, the report said.
Moran said the U.S. Navy is working to make sure allies know that the ships will still patrol traditional areas and is also addressing logistics and family liaison issues for new deployment procedures.
Vice Admiral Michael Noonan, commander of the Royal Australian Navy, also spoke at the event, saying that the Australian military could work seamlessly with the U.S. aircraft carrier battle group.
He said that situation will continue as the Royal Australian Navy plans to purchase nine more frigates equipped with the Aegis combat system.
From October 5, many airlines will raise or resume fuel surcharges, and air travel will have to be increased from next Friday
Yesterday, Lucky Air, Okay Air and other airlines announced that starting from October 5, 2018 (the date of ticket issuance), the fuel surcharge for domestic routes will be 20 yuan per passenger for routes below 800 kilometers (inclusive), and 30 yuan for each passenger on routes above 800 kilometers.
Lucky Air, Okay Air and other companies announced that from 0:00 on October 5, 2018 (the date of ticket issuance), the fuel surcharge standard for domestic routes below 800 kilometers (inclusive) will be increased from 10 yuan per person to 20 yuan per person, and the fuel surcharge standard for domestic routes above 800 kilometers will be increased from 10 yuan per person to 30 yuan per person.
Children and military police disabled persons are both 10 yuan per person, and infants continue to be exempted.
According to the relevant person in charge of Ctrip's air ticket, the airline has indicated in the notice that the fuel surcharge will be charged based on the original ticket issuance date, and the fuel surcharge will not be refunded or compensated when the ticket is reissued.
This means that domestic tickets issued before October 5 do not need to pay the fuel surcharge according to the new standard if they are changed to October 5 (inclusive) or later.
Since June 5, 2018, many airlines such as Air China, China Eastern Airlines, Hainan Airlines, Shanghai Airlines, Spring Airlines, Shenzhen Airlines, West Airlines, Okay Air and many other airlines have resumed charging fuel surcharges for domestic routes that have been cancelled for three years, at a standard of 10 yuan per person.
This time, Lucky Air and Okay Air took the lead in announcing an increase in fuel surcharges, and as of press time, there has been no news of the four major domestic airlines announcing follow-up adjustments.
It is also understood that the Hong Kong Civil Aviation Department stipulates that airlines can decide whether to charge fuel surcharges at their discretion from November.
Cathay Pacific first announced on September 27 that it would reintroduce fuel surcharges from November 2.
According to the Cathay Pacific website, all tickets issued or reissued by Cathay Pacific and Cathay Dragon on or after 2 November will include a fuel surcharge of $652 for long-haul flights between Hong Kong and the South West Pacific, North America, Europe, the Middle East and India and Africa, and $146 for short-haul flights.
Fees apply to all ticket types, on a per-sector basis, and are inclusive of the price quoted across all Cathay Pacific direct channels.
On the eve of the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China, Chinese Premier Li Keqiang met with the new envoys of 29 countries and regions in the Great Hall of the People on the afternoon of the 30th.
Li Keqiang shook hands with the envoys in China one by one and had cordial conversations.
Li Keqiang welcomed the envoys to China to take up their new posts and asked them to convey his sincere greetings and best wishes to the leaders and people of the countries concerned, as well as the leaders of relevant institutions.
Li Keqiang spoke positively of China's good relations with other countries and regions, stressed that China is committed to enhancing bilateral political mutual trust, deepening practical cooperation, and strengthening coordination and cooperation in international and regional affairs.
The Chinese Government is willing to provide convenience and support to the envoys in the performance of their duties.
Li Keqiang pointed out that China adheres to the path of peaceful development and unswervingly promotes economic globalization.
This year marks the 40 th anniversary of China's reform and opening up, and as the largest developing country in the world, we are willing to achieve common development with other countries in the process of further opening up.
Against the backdrop of rising protectionism and unilateralism, we stand ready to work with all parties to continue to consolidate and strengthen partnerships, promote synergistic development strategies based on the principles of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit, promote cooperation in the Belt and Road Initiative based on the principle of extensive consultation, joint contribution and shared benefits, work together to defend multilateralism and free trade, jointly build an open world economy, and inject new impetus into the stable and balanced development of the world economy.
The envoys of various countries and institutions in China warmly congratulated the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China, conveyed the greetings of the leaders of their respective countries and institutions to the Chinese leaders and people, and said that China has made remarkable achievements in development and believes that further deepening reform and expanding opening-up will bring more development opportunities to the world in the future.
We are willing to play a positive role in promoting friendly cooperation between our respective countries and regions and China and better achieving mutual benefit and win-win results.
Subsequently, the envoys of various countries and institutions in China attended the National Day reception at the invitation of Li Keqiang.
State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi attended the event.
Japan's Itochu Corporation on Friday recognized a $1.3 billion impairment loss on its investment in China's CITIC shares, writing down its largest corporate investment deal as it was affected by trade tensions between China and the United States.
A man walks past the headquarters of Marubeni Corporation in Tokyo, Japan, May 2016.
Marubeni, for its part, said the trade war had hit its U.S. grain unit, Gao Hong, who had suspended financial transactions in agriculture.
Some Japanese heavy equipment manufacturers and telecommunications companies have warned about the impact of Sino-US trade frictions when they announced their latest results, and now these Japanese trading companies have also joined the ranks.
The United States and China have imposed tariffs on hundreds of billions of dollars of each other's goods, and US President Donald Trump has threatened to expand the tariffs to cover all more than $500 billion of Chinese goods exported to the United States if the dispute cannot be resolved.
Tsuyoshi Hachimura, ITOCHU Corporation's chief financial officer, said the impact of the trade dispute on China's economy next year could be even greater.
ITOCHU Corporation and Thailand's C.P. Group invested US$10 billion in CITIC in 2015 for a 20% stake.
Hachimura said ITOCHU posted a 143.3 billion yen ($1.3 billion) loss on the stake because it did not believe that CITIC's share price would recover in the near future.
ITOCHU Corporation maintained its profit forecast for the fiscal year ending March 31, 2019 at JPY 500 billion.
China imposed a 25% import tariff on U.S. soybeans in July to counter Washington's efforts in the trade friction.
"Our grain business has been hit by the U.S.-China trade friction," said Marubeni Finance Chief Officer, Nobuhiro Yabe.
He said that Gao Hong had stopped financial transactions in his account since September.
In a statement on Friday, Mr. Pat Burke, a spokesman for Mr. Gao, said the company's move was "in accordance with internal policy restrictions and due to a lack of market opportunity." ”
He also said that the suspension of financial transactions will not lead to a loss of jobs.
Marubeni maintained its annual profit forecast of 230 billion yen, supported by its pulp and paper and power generation businesses.
Sumitomo Corporation on Thursday reported a 16 percent increase in profits between April and September, stressing that "U.S. trade issues with China have led to uncertain prospects." ”
Mitsubishi Corporation on Friday raised its annual profit forecast to a record level, attributed to higher coking coal production and higher commodity prices such as oil and coal.
Mitsubishi Corporation also announced a new business plan to increase its profit for the fiscal year ending March 31, 2022 to 900 billion yen (US$7.98 billion) from an estimated 640 billion yen this year.
