With active treatment, the survival rate of preterm infants born at 29 weeks and above in China has reached 98%, which has reached the level of developed countries.
Chinanews.com, Shanghai, September 30 (Chen Jing, Luo Yanqian) The National Children's Medical Center and the Children's Hospital Affiliated to Fudan University disclosed on the 30th that they introduced advanced Canadian methods in the "China NICU Inpatient Prematurity Infant Prognostic Quality Improvement Project" led by them.
The results of the project showed that the survival rate of preterm infants at 29 weeks and above in China reached 98% after active treatment, which has reached the level of developed countries, but there is still great room for improvement in the survival rate of preterm infants of very small gestational age and preterm infants without complications.
For nearly 20 years, the Chinese government has been concerned about the treatment of newborns.
At present, the infant mortality rate in Shanghai has dropped to 3.71 per thousand, which is significantly lower than the national average and has reached the advanced level of developed countries.
The "Prognosis Quality Improvement Project for Preterm Infants in the China NICU" has greatly improved the quality of life of preterm infants through four years of unremitting efforts.
Professor Cao Yun, director of the Neonatal Intensive Care Unit (NICU) of the Children's Hospital of Fudan University, told reporters that while improving the survival rate of premature infants, it is of great significance to pay attention to reducing the quality of survival of premature infants, reducing the incidence of complications, improving the prognosis of neurodevelopment, and improving the overall outcome of children.
Through four years of unremitting efforts, the "China NICU Prognosis Quality Improvement Project for Premature Infants" has included tens of thousands of premature infants with a gestational age of 33 weeks and below, which has reduced the mortality rate of preterm infants with small gestational age and small birth weight by 1/3 in China, and the incidence of serious complications in preterm infants has been significantly reduced, which has greatly improved the quality of life of premature infants.
Through the establishment of a national neonatal quality improvement cooperation network and the introduction of collaborative quality improvement concepts, the project radiates 25 cooperative hospitals in China to establish a complete, systematic and effective collaborative quality improvement method suitable for domestic national conditions to improve the prognosis of preterm infants and improve the level of neonatal treatment.
The Children's Hospital of Fudan University is working with the national neonatology department to formulate guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections based on the experience accumulated in the project, so as to provide reference and guidance for the standardized diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections in China.
It is understood that in the "China Premature Infant Prognostic Quality Improvement Project", the pediatric hospital introduced the EPIQ method into 25 large NICUs in 19 provinces across the country, and is committed to solving the problem of infection of premature infants that plagues neonatal intensive care units in China.
After more than 10 years of continuous improvement, the uncomplicated survival rate of preterm infants in Canada has increased by about one-third, and Canada is now one of the countries with the best prognosis for preterm infants in the world.
The EPIQ method has now been used in all NICUs in Canada and has been adopted in six countries.
According to the pediatric hospital, the results of the study showed that after two years of EPIQ intervention, preterm infant infections decreased by 35%, and antibiotic use decreased by 20%.
In the future, the Children's Hospital of Fudan University will continue to promote and implement this method nationwide, focusing on comprehensively reducing the incidence of all complications of preterm infants and improving the quality of neonatal treatment across the country.
At present, it is an indisputable fact that there are differences and heterogeneity in the level of treatment in different regions of China.
According to Professor Cao Yun, as an important construction unit of the National Children's Medical Center, the pediatric hospital will play a leading role, and this study covers Xinjiang, Guizhou, Gansu, Shaanxi and other western provinces, in order to gradually promote the homogeneity and standardization of neonatal treatment nationwide.
It is understood that the Children's Hospital of Fudan University is working with the national neonatology department to formulate guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections based on the experience accumulated in the project, so as to provide reference and guidance for the standardized diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections in China.
According to reports, in 2019, the China Neonatal Collaboration Network, which is located in the Children's Hospital Affiliated to Fudan University, will work with 63 hospitals across the country to carry out the next stage of national quality improvement, in order to promote the development of the equalization of China's neonatal treatment level.
Wu Jinglei, director of the Shanghai Municipal Health and Family Planning Commission, said that Shanghai can become the center of Asia, not only in research, but also in the construction of the entire service system, and the service quality and service results should have a place in Asia, so as to truly reflect China's medical level.
Xin Zhiping: Building a "Monument to Heroes" in my heart ———— written on the Fifth Martyrs' Day.
On September 30, on the eve of the 69th birthday of the People's Republic of China, we ushered in the fifth Martyrs' Day, and Xi Jinping and other party and state leaders came to Tiananmen Square to attend the ceremony of laying flower baskets to the people's heroes.
At this moment, no matter where you are, please pay tribute to the martyrs.
Anniversaries are revisited, but also awakened.
Turning over the thick history, behind the name of every martyr is a fresh life.
They also have fiery youth, sincere love, and concerned families.
However, because they firmly believe that "the doctrine of our faith is the truth of the universe," they are willing to sacrifice everything they have in order to "save the next generation from suffering."
