Let advocating heroes, defending heroes, learning heroes, and caring for heroes become a common practice, and let the spirit of heroes and martyrs be integrated into the blood of the nation, and the "Heroes Monument" will stand majestically between heaven and earth and in the depths of people's hearts.
BRUSSELS, Sept 28 (Reuters) - The European Union took a non-confrontational stance against Italy on Friday after it flouted its demands and surprised markets with a massive budget deficit plan, but it may take a more aggressive stance if Italy sticks to too bold targets.
Italy's Eurosceptic government is targeting a budget deficit equivalent to 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) over the next three years, suggesting that there has been no debt reduction despite deficit reduction requirements.
"We have no interest in the crisis between the European Commission and Italy," said Moskovisi, the European Commission's executive committee member for economic affairs, and his cautious response as the EU's proposals and sanctions are likely to have little impact on Italy.
EU officials and diplomats remain hopeful that market forces will persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan before it formally submits it to the European Commission in mid-October.
The euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday after the government announced its plans, and Italian bond yields hit their highest level in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the European Commission is likely to veto Italy's draft budget, something it has never done to any country.
European Commission Vice President Dombrovsky later told a meeting in Riga, Latvia, on Friday that Italy's current fiscal plan "does not seem to be in line with the Stability and Growth Pact," referring to the EU's fiscal rules.
But he did not say what the EU's reaction would be.
