Xinhua News Agency, Fuzhou, October 1 (Reporter Tai Xiaoan) On October 1, the "Fujian Provincial High-speed Railway Safety Management Regulations" was officially implemented.
The regulations propose that within 500 meters on each side of the high-speed rail power line wire, it is forbidden to fly kites, balloons, Kong Ming lanterns, aircraft and other floating objects and small aircraft.
On the basis of the "Railway Law of the People's Republic of China" and the "Regulations on the Administration of Railway Safety" and other higher-level laws, according to the geographical and climatic characteristics of Fujian Province, supplementary provisions are made on the prohibited and restricted behaviors that affect the safety of high-speed rail, and the construction and tree planting along the high-speed rail are regulated, and the subject and scope of supervision of high-speed rail are further clarified, and the responsibilities and legal responsibilities of law enforcement and supervision are clarified.
In view of the frequent occurrence of strong winds along the coast of Fujian Province, and the safety of light building (structure) materials and light floating objects along the high-speed rail are blown into the high-speed railway, it is stipulated that within 500 meters on both sides of the high-speed rail power line conductor, it is forbidden to raise and fly kites, balloons, Kong Ming lanterns, paramotors, aircraft and other aerial floating objects and small aircraft.
In addition, the owner or user of light objects such as plastic greenhouses, color steel plates, and sunshade nets along the high-speed railway, as well as low-altitude floating objects, plastic protective films and other light objects generated during the construction process, shall take reinforcement and protective measures to prevent endangering the safety of high-speed railways.
In view of the characteristics of Fujian Province being located in hilly areas and having many high-speed railway tunnels, it is stipulated that the opinions of railway construction units or railway transport enterprises shall be solicited for the construction of mountain ponds, reservoirs, dams, excavation of rivers, trunk canals, drilling wells and other behaviors that may affect the safety of tunnels within 200 meters on both sides of the center line above the high-speed rail tunnel.
At the same time, those who violate the relevant responsibilities of the "Regulations" will be ordered by the public security organs to make corrections; if the circumstances are more serious, they shall be fined not less than 5,000 yuan but not more than 10,000 yuan for units, and not more than 200 yuan but not more than 500 yuan for individuals; if the circumstances are serious, they shall be fined not less than 10,000 yuan but not more than 30,000 yuan for units, and not more than 500 yuan but not more than 1,000 yuan for individuals.
and where losses are caused, they shall be liable for compensation in accordance with law.
It is understood that with the rapid development of railway construction, the high-speed railway mileage of 200 kilometers per hour and above in Fujian Province has reached 1,516 kilometers, realizing the city-to-city bullet train, and it is expected that the railway lines with a speed of 200 kilometers per hour and above in Fujian will reach 2,150 kilometers in the next five years.
The implementation of this regulation will standardize the safety management of high-speed rail in Fujian Province, further implement the responsibilities of local government departments, coordinate railway and local forces, work together to ensure the safety of high-speed rail, and improve the safety prevention and control system of high-speed rail in Fujian Province.
HONG KONG, Nov 5 (Reuters) - China Resources Beer (Holdings) Co Ltd (0291.HK), China's largest beer ————producer, announced on Monday that it has acquired six breweries established by Heineken (HEIN.AS) in mainland China and the entire issued share capital of Heineken Hong Kong through its subsidiary China Resources Snow Beer, for a total consideration of about HK$2.355 billion.
At the same time, the Company entered into a trademark licensing agreement with Heineken to authorize CR Snow to use the relevant Heineken® trademark in Chinese mainland, Hong Kong and Macau to produce, market, distribute and sell licensed products for a period of 20 years, which will be renewed on the same terms and conditions for a period of 10 years at a time until the termination of the termination clause of the trademark license agreement.
China Resources Beer announced in August this year that its direct controlling shareholder, China Resources Group (Beer) Co., Ltd., had reached an equity cooperation agreement with Heineken involving up to about HK$28.5 billion.
At the same time, CR Beer and Heineken entered into a long-term strategic cooperation arrangement, which includes the acquisition of Heineken's existing businesses in China, Hong Kong and Macau, and the integration with CR Beer's beer business in China.
This transaction is a further implementation of the cooperation agreement.
CR Beer said the transaction with Heineken provides the group with an important strategic and long-term development and value enhancement opportunity to expand into the premium beer market, and the resulting long-term relationship between the two parties will be highly complementary.
China Resources Beer closed at HK$28.85 on Friday, down nearly 4.5% over the past month.
Indonesia is devastated after the earthquake and tsunami, and the number of victims may be as high as thousands-Chinanews.com
According to comprehensive reports, a shallow earthquake of magnitude 7.5 struck Sulawesi, Indonesia on September 28, triggering a 6-meter-high tsunami.
The death toll rose to 832, the national disaster response department announced on September 30, mainly in the capital Palu and Donggara district near the epicenter.
Vice President Cara noted that the death toll could be in the thousands, as the casualty figures remain uncounted in some of the affected areas.
The powerful earthquake and tsunami that struck Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province on the afternoon of September 28 have killed 832 people.
Thousands of buildings collapsed and 2.4 million people were affected
Palu was devastated by thousands of buildings and broken roads, with an estimated 2.4 million people affected, according to authorities.
Only 24 guests escaped safely from a hotel located on the local coast, and an estimated 50 to 60 people were trapped in the rubble, with cries for help being heard from the scene at the scene, and rescuers managed to rescue a young woman on September 30.
To ensure the safety of the trapped people, the authorities were unable to use heavy machinery to remove the rubble, and the search and rescue process was slow.
A shopping mall in the city also collapsed, and hundreds of residents rushed to the scene to wait for news from relatives and friends.
Many residents used social media platforms to post posts to find their lost relatives and friends.
On September 30, local time, a hotel collapsed in Balu City, Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, and rescue work began.
10,000 people in Palu to be rescued, and the whereabouts of 5 foreigners are unknown
Authorities said there were about 10,000 people waiting for help in Palu, scattered across 50 locations.
It is reported that 71 foreigners were in Palu at the time of the earthquake, and 66 of them are temporarily known to be safe, including 21 Chinese citizens, and the whereabouts of the remaining 2 Frenchmen, 2 Malaysian tourists and 1 South Korean are unknown.
The Chinese Embassy in Indonesia is verifying the situation of Chinese citizens in the disaster area through various channels, and has not yet received any reports of casualties among Chinese citizens.
Communications remain disrupted in Donggara district, near the epicenter, and 11 people have been temporarily killed, but no further details are available.
According to footage from the scene, the coastal area and port of Donggara County were badly damaged, a large number of buildings were swept away, and bodies were scattered everywhere, and Red Cross rescue teams were heading to the local search and rescue team.
Indonesia's president inspected the disaster and said that reconstruction work should be carried out as soon as possible
The roads in Palu and Donggara were severely damaged, and Palu airport was only open to planes carrying relief supplies on September 30 to allow relief supplies and personnel to arrive as quickly as possible and to remove the seriously injured.
Power is still without power in many local hospitals, and the injured are being treated outdoors.
More than 10,000 victims have been admitted to shelters, and some are afraid to go home for fear of aftershocks, preferring to spend the night outdoors.
Following the collapse of a prison in Palu in the earthquake, triggering the escape of hundreds of prisoners, more than 100 inmates in Dongara County took advantage of the chaos caused by the earthquake and set fire to the detention center.
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, who visited Palu on September 30, pointed out that it is very difficult to solve a large number of problems in a short period of time, including the restoration of communications.
He appealed for patience and said the authorities would start reconstruction work as soon as possible.
On the other hand, Indonesia's finance minister announced that the government has allocated IDR 560 billion for disaster relief.
A human case of H5N6 avian influenza has been confirmed in Guangdong Province
According to the Health Bureau, according to the latest notification from the mainland health authorities, a human case of H5N6 avian influenza has been confirmed in Guangdong Province.
The Health Bureau urges residents to avoid contact with birds and pay attention to personal and food hygiene.
According to the information, the patient is a 22-year-old male living in Baiyun District, Guangzhou City, Guangdong Province, who developed fever and other symptoms on September 25 and was admitted to hospital for treatment on September 26.
Prior to the onset of illness, the patient had slaughtered and eaten live poultry.
Since April 2014, there have been confirmed cases of H5N6 avian influenza in Sichuan, Guangdong, Yunnan, Hubei, Hunan, Anhui and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
The Health Bureau will continue to maintain close liaison with the health authorities of the country and neighbouring regions and the World Health Organization (WHO) to closely monitor the epidemic situation in various places and in Macao.
To prevent human infection with avian influenza, the Health Bureau wishes to pay attention to the following:
Avoid contact with birds or their secretions and excreta, and wash hands immediately if they do;
Do not buy or carry birds that have not been quarantined;
Do not consume undercooked poultry meat, offal, blood products and eggs;
Pay attention to personal hygiene and wash hands frequently;
If you have symptoms such as fever, cough, or difficulty breathing, you should wear a mask, seek medical attention as soon as possible, and explain your travel history and animal contact history to your doctor.
