The new U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade deal would preserve U.S. President Donald Trump's ability to enforce his threat of 25 percent tariffs on imported cars, while essentially exempting passenger cars, pickup trucks and auto parts imported from Canada and Mexico, according to a trade deal ancillary arrangement unveiled Monday.
If Trump imposes so-called "Chapter 232" tariffs on cars for national security reasons, both Mexico and Canada will have a quota of 2.6 million duty-exempt passenger cars exported to the United States each year.
Under the ancillary arrangement, pickup trucks manufactured in both countries will be fully exempt from tariffs.
If Trump imposes tariffs on automobiles, Mexico will receive a $108 billion annual auto parts exemption quota, and Canada will receive a $32.4 billion quota.
Both quotas are well above the current production levels of both countries, providing room for growth in both countries' exports.
WASHINGTON/Mexico, Sept 28 (Reuters) - After days of debate, US President Donald Trump's administration and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve trade policy differences, raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is expected to maintain its tripartite format, Mexico said on Friday.
While details are lacking, the apparent progress is enough to prompt the Mexican and U.S. governments to abruptly halt plans to publish the text of a trade agreement between the two countries, giving Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexican President-elect Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador told reporters in Mexico that the U.S. government has made a new counter-proposal to the Canadian government and said he will continue to push for all three countries to participate in NAFTA.
Mexico's economy minister, Ildefonso Guajardo, said the submission of the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement to Mexico and the U.S. for legislation had been delayed as the Canadian and U.S. governments tried to reach an agreement "very seriously."
"In the next 48 hours, we will know whether we will reach a text of a tripartite agreement or if we will have to publish the text of the bipartite agreement," Guajardo said. ”
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian counterparts "specifically requested" that the release of the text be delayed.
A spokesperson for the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement or U.S.-Canada negotiations.
Officials from the Office of the Prime Minister and the Foreign Minister of Canada did not respond to requests for comment on counterproposals.
According to foreign media reports, in a nursery center on the outskirts of Pretoria, the capital of South Africa, two lion cubs are playing together, and it is difficult to see anything unusual, but they are actually unique.
The University of Pretoria announced: "This is the first ever artificial insemination of a lion cub – the first couple in the world. ”
Scientists at the university are studying the reproductive system of female African lions.
Gans Wintert, director of the Institute of Mammal Research at the University of Pretoria, said the two lion cubs, one male and one female, were quite healthy and normal, born on August 25.
His team finally achieved this breakthrough after 18 months of intensive experimentation.
Speaking to the media, Ganswinter said: "We collect sperm from a healthy male lion. ”
Next, the researchers waited for the lioness to reach the right level of hormones before artificially inseminating it.
Ganswinter said: "Fortunately, it turned out to be a success. ”
The researchers, he said, "made several attempts, but unexpectedly, didn't take much effort."
He said the breakthrough was reproducible, and scientists hope to use the technology to save endangered big cats.
According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature, lions have become extinct in 26 African countries, and the total number of lions surviving in the wild has plummeted by 43% in the past 20 years to only about 20,000.
African lions are classified as vulnerable by this organization.
"If we don't do something about these animals, they're going to go extinct," Ganswinter said. ”
He said the new technology does not require lions to be reared, but simply sperm is injected into fertile lionesses, as is the case with captive elephants in North America and Europe.
South Korea's exports fell by the most in more than two years in September, but analysts blamed the decline on fewer working days and said global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising trade tensions between China and the United States.
Indeed, South Korea's average daily exports increased last month.
In addition, the preliminary data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first weeks of September before the long holiday.
South Korea's exports fell by the most year-on-year in September since July 2016, larger than the 5.7 percent decline estimated by 11 analysts polled by Reuters.
Preliminary data released on Monday showed exports of $50.6 billion in September, down from $51.2 billion in August.
South Korea's exports to China rose 7.8 percent in September, the 23rd straight month of expansion, despite fears that the growing U.S.-China trade dispute could hurt other export-dependent Chinese neighbors as well.
South Korea's exports to the U.S. fell 11.8 percent due to a decline in sales of petroleum products.
Overseas sales of memory chips and petroleum products in South Korea increased by 28.3% and 13.5%, respectively, despite concerns that the so-called chip "supercycle" may have peaked.
"However, the impact of the trade conflict will be difficult to avoid, as South Korea is heavily dependent on the U.S. and Chinese markets for its exports. ”
Imports fell 2.1 percent to $40.8 billion, not as good as the 3.1 percent increase estimated in a Reuters poll.
The preliminary trade surplus in September was $9.7 billion, up from $6.9 billion in August.
According to the Ministry of Industry, thanks to the United States and European Union countries, the global manufacturing industry will remain strong, which is a favorable factor for South Korea's exports.
The statement pointed out that "the increase in export prices caused by the rise in oil prices will also be beneficial to exports in the second half of this year." ”
"However, the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with the increased market volatility following the US interest rate hike, is a negative pressure on exports. ”
Exports increased to $2.6 billion per working day in September, compared with $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea's Mid-Autumn Festival falls on September 24-26 this year, so there are only 19.5 working days in September, four fewer than the same period last year.
South Korea's exports from January to September increased by 4.7% from the same period last year.
South Korea's manufacturing activity picked up in September, according to the Nikkei/Markit PMI, but was supported by domestic orders, which could cloud the outlook for exports as orders from China and Japan fell.
