First of all, the essence of the Korean Peninsula issue remains unchanged, and the key to achieving peace on the Korean Peninsula is to properly and balancedly resolve the legitimate security concerns of all parties, rather than blindly putting pressure on the other side and blindly emphasizing one's own demands.
Second, in the dialogue on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, the parties concerned still have differences on the steps and ways to realize the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.
At the UN Security Council's open meeting on the Korean Peninsula issue held at the UN headquarters in New York a few days ago, the different voices of all sides on the issue of sanctions against the DPRK once again highlighted that these two points on the Korean Peninsula issue "have not changed."
