In order to ensure safety, the scenic spot is temporarily closed during the National Day.
Hukou Waterfall on the Yellow River is the second largest waterfall in China and the largest yellow waterfall in the world.
The Yellow River flows here, the stone walls on both sides of the river stand steeply, and the estuary is as narrow as the mouth of a pot, forming the spirit of "a pot of the Yellow River for a thousand miles".
According to the reporter's understanding, every year from June to October is the Yellow River flood season, starting from July 12, 2018, due to the high water level of the Yellow River, Shanxi Yellow River Hukou Scenic Area began to close one after another, so Hukou Scenic Area has been closed for nearly a month.
Ni Yufeng, chief engineer of the Hukou Scenic Area Management Committee, told the media that this is the longest time in the past 20 years that the high water level of the Yellow River has continued, "It has not been closed for so long before, and in 2017 we closed for 4 days during the flood season, and this year it is nearly a month." ”
It is understood that in order to welcome the "Eleventh" Golden Week, the Hukou Waterfall Scenic Area of the Yellow River in Shanxi Province has also increased personnel arrangements and vehicle maintenance in advance, and even temporary staff employment has been put in place.
According to the "Circular on Doing a Good Job in Flood Prevention and Flood Control Work in the Yellow River during the National Day" issued by the "Ming Chuan Telegram from the Office of the Yellow River Flood Control and Drought Relief General Headquarters," Qinghai, Gansu, Ningxia, Inner Mongolia, Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan, and Shandong provinces are required to do a good job in flood prevention work on the Yellow River during the National Day.
At present, the flow of the main stream of the Yellow River is relatively large, with the flow of the upper reaches of the river being maintained at 2,000-3,000 cubic meters per second, the flow of the middle reaches of the river being maintained at 2,500-3,500 cubic meters per second, and the flow of the lower reaches of the river being maintained at the order of 3,000 cubic meters per second.
Influenza vaccination services are provided at health centres and health posts during the National Day holiday
The Health Bureau has ordered 150,000 doses of quadrivalent influenza vaccine for 2018-2019 this year, and priority is given to high-risk groups for free vaccination at this stage.
In addition to the above-mentioned facilitation measures, the influenza vaccination service hours of all health centres and health stations under the Health Bureau have been extended to 8pm from Monday to Friday since the launch of the programme, and as of 4pm on 30 September, 4,158 people have been vaccinated, compared with more than 3,714 in the same period last year.
The free vaccination targets include the following Macao residents: 6 months to under 18 years old, people aged 50 and above, pregnant women, all people with chronic diseases, including obese people (i.e. those with a body mass index (BMI of 30 or above), as well as staff in residential care homes, nurseries, kindergartens, primary and secondary schools, all health workers, and Macao residents working in gaming and casinos.
At the same time, for other persons deemed necessary by the Health Bureau, including the public sector, the Health Bureau will take the initiative to contact the relevant institutions to obtain the list and the Health Centre will arrange vaccination after the Health Bureau deems it necessary.
In order to facilitate the vaccinated and shorten the waiting time for vaccination, the Health Bureau will send medical staff to secondary schools, primary schools, kindergartens and nurseries in Macao from October to December this year to conduct influenza vaccination for young children, primary and secondary school students, teachers and staff.
Students and children who are unable to participate in the group vaccination can bring their Macao Resident Identity Card, Health Bureau User Card, Influenza Vaccination Card (if any), student card, employee ID card or occupation certificate to the vaccination station or health centre of Conde de de Januário General Hospital from 3 December 2018.
The Health Bureau reminds residents that those who have received influenza vaccine from September 2017 to August 2018 are still required to receive the new season of influenza vaccine from September 2018 onwards as the influenza antigen composition of the 2018-2019 Northern Hemisphere Influenza Vaccine has been updated to target the 2018-2019 winter and summer 2019 seasonal influenza in the Northern Hemisphere.
The peak of influenza in Macao generally occurs from January to March each year, which is later than that in temperate regions (such as northern China and Japan), and the Health Bureau appeals to the elderly, children, pregnant women, obese people and chronic patients, who are more likely to develop complications after influenza infection, as well as those who are in frequent contact with high-risk groups, to get vaccinated as soon as possible.
