TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence among Japan's large manufacturers hit its lowest level in more than a year in the September quarter, according to the Bank of Japan's quarterly Tankan survey report released on Monday, as companies were under pressure from rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affecting production.
The survey shows little that escalating global trade frictions have undermined the confidence of large manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-blown trade war has hit companies' business prospects and could threaten corporate capital expenditures.
Buoyant capital spending is a bright spot in the Japanese economy.
The survey calls into question the BOJ's view that a solid economic expansion will help accelerate inflation to its 2% target, despite signs that businesses are gradually passing costs on to customers.
"Amid concerns about the global trade war, manufacturing confidence has stalled due to slowing exports and weak factory production," said Nam Wuzhi, chief researcher at the China Finance Research Institute.
"Confidence is still high. And with corporate earnings improving and prices rising, I don't think confidence will continue to decline. ”
According to the Tankan survey, the large-scale manufacturing sentiment index fell to positive 19 in September from positive 21 three months ago, marking the third consecutive quarter of deterioration.
The median estimate for the market is positive 22.
The large non-manufacturing sentiment index fell to positive 22 in September from positive 24 in the June survey, deteriorating for the first time in eight quarters.
The Reuters survey was positive 22.
According to the survey, the large-scale manufacturing and non-manufacturing prosperity judgment index is expected to remain stable in December.
Investors are not concerned about the decline in the Tankan Corporate Sentiment Judgment Index, and the Nikkei Stock Index. N225 rose to a 27-year high on Monday as the yen's continued depreciation helped improve the outlook for Japanese companies' export earnings.
Solid capital expenditures.
Despite the decline in business confidence, the latest Tankan highlights the robustness of corporate capital expenditure plans, helped by renewing production capacity and increasing investment in robotics and automation to cope with labour shortages due to an aging population.
According to the central bank's Tankan survey, large companies plan to increase capital spending by 13.4% in the current fiscal year ending March 2019.
In the previous tankan survey, it was 13.6%.
Minami said that the capital expenditure of all companies is planned to increase by 8.5% this fiscal year, which is close to the pace of Japan's bubble economy era.
"There is still room for further growth in capital spending, given that small businesses have raised their profit estimates from now on, but much will depend on the impact of the trade war on business confidence," he said. ”
The Tankan survey showed a stronger ability for companies to pass on costs, and the output price index of large companies came in at positive 7, a decade-high high, which is an encouraging sign that Japan has made progress in its efforts to combat deflation.
The index, which measures employment conditions in large firms, hit minus 23, the tightest level since 1992, highlighting a tighter job market.
Japan's economy rebounded in the second quarter from the contraction in January-March this year, benefiting from strong business spending.
But the escalation of trade frictions over the summer and supply chain disruptions have clouded the outlook for Japan's export-dependent economy.
