More than nine out of ten Brazilian female voters say presidential candidates do not consider women's needs.
According to the South American Overseas Chinese News Network, data recently released by the Brazilian National Geographic Institute (IBGE) shows that more than 90% of Brazilian women do not believe that the needs of women are considered by presidential candidates.
At present, the number of women in Brazil has reached 107 million, and if all Brazilian women were gathered to form a country, the country would rank 13th in the world in terms of population, more than twice the population of Spain.
In Brazil, women make up 52 percent of the electorate, while men make up 48 percent, and although women make up a very high percentage of the electorate, only 10 percent of Brazil's Congress is women.
Out of 193 countries in the world, Brazil ranks only 154th in terms of women's participation in politics, higher than Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of power struggles, Brazilian women still haven't succeeded in gaining their rights.
Brazilian sociologist Natalia Mori argues that the reason for this phenomenon is the result of a combination of ancient patriarchal societies, racism and capitalist values.
"Politics is supposed to be a society in which citizens claim civil rights, identity, access to public goods, and are made up of multiple social groups. But Brazilian politics is monopolized by one group, and the majority of the population is not represented. ”
A previous study conducted by the Brazilian Locomotive Research Institute (Locomotiva) also pointed out that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that elected politicians represent their rights, 90% of Brazilian women do not agree with the decisions made by politicians, and 93% do not agree with the current government's governance policies.
"We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament, and Brazil's political system is still affected by inequality. To this day, there is still a high level of gender, class and racial discrimination in the Brazilian political sphere. Natalia Mori said.
Despite women's lack of rights, the majority of Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
