Systemic lupus erythematosus is a chronic and intractable disease that affects multiple organs throughout the body, and was once considered an "incurable disease" in the past.
Because of its unclear pathogenesis, difficult diagnosis and treatment, and lack of effective treatment, it cannot be cured.
Recently, a joint team of Liu Wanli, a researcher at the School of Life Sciences at Tsinghua University, and Li Zhanguo, director of the Rheumatology and Immunology Center of Peking University People's Hospital, discovered that there is a molecular variant in human immunoglobulin that increases susceptibility to systemic lupus erythematosus, and this variant is involved in the regulation of immune B cells.
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the human body is an important cause of the onset of systemic lupus erythematosus.
According to Sun Xiaolin, one of the authors of the article and Peking University People's Hospital, Li Zhanguo's team collected nearly 2,000 large samples of systemic lupus erythematosus patients and conducted research, and found that patients with immunoglobulin mutations produced pathogenic cells and a wide variety and number of autoantibodies, and the incidence and severity of inflammation such as nephritis, arthritis, serositis, and vasculitis increased significantly.
Through a variety of research methods such as immune cell tracing, animal experiments, and sequencing, Liu Wanli's team discovered the pathogenic mechanism of immune signaling pathways activated by mutations of immune molecules and the secretion of various autoantibodies by B cells.
The reporter learned that the two teams joined forces, gave full play to their respective advantages, and realized the close combination of basic research and clinical application.
Liu Wanli's team is committed to the research of B lymphocyte immune recognition and immune activation, while Li Zhanguo's team has been engaged in clinical research on systemic lupus erythematosus for a long time.
"This study is one of the results of the collaboration between the two teams for many years, and it is also the first time that the academic community has recognized the mechanism that immunoglobulin gene abnormalities will induce systemic lupus erythematosus, laying a solid foundation for further academic research and clinical targeted therapy. ”
