Since the mid-2000s, as China's demand for oilseeds has grown, North Dakota farmer Paul Thomas has grown more and more soybeans in his fields.
That shift peaked this year, when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres, an unprecedented scale.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch to corn and wheat, which were previously staple crops in U.S. agriculture, in 2019.
For the first time in 35 years, U.S. farmers are planting more soybeans than corn this year.
The plan to switch to other food crops comes because U.S. farmers are struggling to sell soybeans against the backdrop of U.S. President Donald Trump's trade war with China.
China typically buys about 60% of U.S. soybeans exported, but the trade war has seen almost zero purchases of U.S. soybeans in recent months, sending soybean prices to a decade-low low.
Thomas plans to grow more wheat next year, hoping to earn more by reducing his dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Thomas said soybean prices were "a hard hit for us".
Without Chinese demand, he said, the spot price of soybeans near his farm is $7.10 per bushel, while the price necessary to cover the cost is $8.50.
U.S. farmers have recorded record soybean acreage this year, and their harvest is on track for record highs.
At such a momentous moment, they were hit by a trade war.
In response to Trump's tariffs on imports of Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on imports of U.S. soybeans in July.
The USDA will release its first estimate of next year's acreage, which is expected to include consideration of tariff implications.
This estimate is expected to confirm the expectation of a reduction in soybean plantings by private institutions.
Informa Economics projected corn acreage to increase 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) in 2019 and soybean acreage to 83 million acres in 2019, according to a report seen by Reuters.
Informa also expects a 4 percent increase in wheat acreage in the United States.
The area of soybeans planted before the retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, about 15 million acres higher than 10 years ago.
Corn acreage has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres, and wheat acreage is 47.8 million acres this year, near a 100-year low.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Plantation Association, has nearly half of his family's 3,600 acres planted this year, but plans to cut it back in the future.
He said it could increase corn acreage by up to 20 percent on his farm in northern Illinois; The state is the largest soybean-growing state in the United States.
Soybeans have lower yields per acre than corn, but they also require less fertilizer, which makes soybeans generally cheaper to grow.
If farmers switch to final corn, it could raise costs, but it will benefit some businesses, including Andersons Inc fertilizer sellers.
Andersons CEO Pat Bowe told Reuters that he expects switching to corn will benefit fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from farmers' switch to corn.
