Five people were killed when an illegal migrant boat sank in the waters of the Aegean Sea in Turkey.
Istanbul, Sept. 30 (Xinhua) -- According to Turkish media reports on the 30th, an inflatable boat carrying illegal immigrants capsized in the waters of the Aegean Sea in Turkey on the same day, killing at least five people.
According to the report, the inflatable boat, which was originally scheduled to go to a Greek island, sank near the Enez region of Edirne Province in northwestern Turkey on the same day, and the reason for the sinking is unknown.
At the moment, it is not known the number of illegal immigrants on board the sunken inflatable boat.
As it is estimated that there are still people trapped at sea, the relevant search and rescue operations are still continuing.
The Aegean Sea was once the preferred route for illegal immigrants to cross to the European continent via Turkey.
Turkey's control of the passage under an agreement with the European Union in March 2016 has significantly reduced the number of people smuggled through this channel.
But since the beginning of this year, the number of smugglers on this channel has rebounded.
According to the official website of the Nobel Prize, at 11:30 p.m. local time on the 1st in Stockholm, Sweden, American immunologist James Allison and Japanese immunologist Yu Honjo won the 2018 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of cancer therapies that inhibit negative immune regulation.
According to Japanese media reports, the 76-year-old Honjo, the 26th Japanese to win the Nobel Prize and the fifth to win a prize in physiology or medicine, learned of his award in his laboratory.
It is reported that Yu Honjo was born on January 27, 1942, is a Japanese doctor, medical scientist, foreign member of the US National Academy of Sciences, a member of the Japanese Academy of Sciences, and is currently a visiting professor at Kyoto University.
In 1992, he discovered the T cell inhibitory receptor PD-1, and in 2013, he pioneered cancer immunotherapy, which ranked first among the top 10 scientific breakthroughs of the year by Science.
On September 21, 2016, Yu Honjo was selected for that year's Citation Laureate Award and was hailed as "one of the closest Japanese people to the Nobel Prize".
